      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Electrostatic potential maps of a typical amide (acetamide) and an acyl azide (acetyl azide) are shown. Which of the two do you think is more reactive in nucleophilic acyl substitution reactions? Explain.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaDBYIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--edbb6ba5d965df053cce34b36ae21d43957cfbb5/OChem_21_EC_025.jpg\" alt=\"The electrostatic potential map and structure of acetamide and acetyl azide. The azide has a carbonyl group with a methyl group on one side and a chain of three nitrogen atoms on the other side. The nitrogens are double bonded to each other.\">",
